    <section class="cb-history" aria-label="Campbell history at a glance">
      <span class="cb-history-label">Before Silicon Valley</span>
      <h2 class="cb-history-heading">Campbell was the Orchard City.</h2>
      <p class="cb-history-sub">Eight turning points that built today's town — from a wheat farm bought for a dollar an acre to the courtroom decision that still gets cited in mall free-speech cases. "The Orchard City" is still the official motto.</p>

      <div class="cb-history-timeline">
        <article class="cb-history-card">
          <span class="cb-history-year">1851</span>
          <h3 class="cb-history-title">Benjamin Campbell buys 160 acres</h3>
          <p class="cb-history-desc">He pays roughly <strong>$1 per acre</strong> for wheat-and-hay land where downtown stands today. He works it for 27 years before selling — and the place quietly takes his name.</p>
        </article>

        <article class="cb-history-card">
          <span class="cb-history-year">1878</span>
          <h3 class="cb-history-title">Sells the farm to a railroad</h3>
          <p class="cb-history-desc">The South Pacific Coast Railroad pays <strong>$5/acre</strong> and lays track through the property. A depot, drying yards, and the original "Campbell's Place" cluster up around the line.</p>
        </article>

        <article class="cb-history-card">
          <span class="cb-history-year">1895</span>
          <h3 class="cb-history-title">Bank of Campbell opens</h3>
          <p class="cb-history-desc">The oldest commercial building in town goes up downtown. It's still standing — and the same shell was later converted into a 1938 movie house and then the Gaslighter Theater.</p>
        </article>

        <article class="cb-history-card">
          <span class="cb-history-year">1925</span>
          <h3 class="cb-history-title">The Ainsley House is built</h3>
          <p class="cb-history-desc">John Ainsley, who runs a fruit cannery in town, finishes an <strong>English Tudor</strong> next to his orchard. Decades later (1990) the whole house is rolled through downtown on flatbeds and restored as a city museum.</p>
        </article>

        <article class="cb-history-card">
          <span class="cb-history-year">1928</span>
          <h3 class="cb-history-title">Water tower goes up</h3>
          <p class="cb-history-desc">A <strong>75,000-gallon</strong> tank perches above downtown — the tallest thing for miles. It stays in service for decades and becomes the town's de facto skyline.</p>
        </article>

        <article class="cb-history-card">
          <span class="cb-history-year">1952</span>
          <h3 class="cb-history-title">Campbell incorporates</h3>
          <p class="cb-history-desc">After a century as an unincorporated farm town, Campbell formally becomes a city on <strong>March 28</strong> — late by Bay Area standards. The first city seal carries an orchard tree.</p>
        </article>

        <article class="cb-history-card">
          <span class="cb-history-year">1969</span>
          <h3 class="cb-history-title">The Pruneyard opens</h3>
          <p class="cb-history-desc">A 36-acre shopping center named for the orchard it paved over. In 1980 the Supreme Court rules in <strong>PruneYard v. Robins</strong> that California malls can't bar peaceful leafletting — still cited today.</p>
        </article>

        <article class="cb-history-card">
          <span class="cb-history-year">2005</span>
          <h3 class="cb-history-title">Light rail arrives</h3>
          <p class="cb-history-desc">VTA's Vasona line opens on <strong>October 1</strong>, with two stops in Campbell. The depot's old railroad alignment matters again for the first time in nearly a century.</p>
        </article>
      </div>

      <p class="cb-history-foot">The orchards are gone, but the names stick: Pruneyard, Orchard Supply, the Heritage Theatre. Every parking lot used to be a row of trees.</p>
